items.synopsis: Days after being threatened by multiple, large bushfires, communities in the state's east are bracing for flooding as heavy rainfall continues feeding into river systems. Follow live.

title.children: Floodwaters inundate homes in Victoria's east after heavy rain swells major rivers

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The three towns under immediate flooding threat are Newry, Tinamba and Tinamba West. Newry is is about 215 kilometres east of Melbourne, and 30 kilometres north-west of Sale. According to the latest census, the town had a population of 451 people. Meanwhile Tinamba and Tinamba West had recorded populations of 358 and 63 respectively.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Where are the towns under threat?

Newry, Tinamba and Tinamba West are close to the regional hub of Sale.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The State Emergency Service (SES) has told the ABC that up to 130 homes may flood at Newry, Tinamba and Tinamba West. A number of homes have already flooded at Newry. SES Deputy Chief Officer David Baker told ABC News Breakfast floodwaters downstream of Lake Glenmaggie on the Macalister River were already impacting Newry, and within the hour they would hit Tinamba and Tinamba West. "We estimate up to around 130 properties may be impacted by this event, hence why we issued an emergency warning late yesterday afternoon which was renewed again during the early hours of the morning," he said. "Our crews, police and CFA, have spent the afternoon and overnight making sure that people are warned to move to higher ground." The deputy chief said he believed people had largely heeded those warnings.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Senior meteorologist Dean Narramore, from the Bureau of Meteorology, told the ABC that in some parts of Victoria's east, after 150-200mm of rainfall yesterday, a further 40-50mm has fallen overnight. He said some areas had seen isolated falls exceeding 250mm. "Because of that we've seen rivers continue to rise overnight," he said. "Early this morning, we're looking at major flooding occurring on the Macalister, the Mitchell, and the Ovens and King River." He said there may be major flooding downstream of Lake Glenmaggie this morning and this afternoon, and moderate to possibly major flooding on the Mitchell River that could affect Bairnsdale later this morning and into the afternoon.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: In a bid to counter the spreading of disinformation about the referendum, the Australian Electoral Commission (AEC) has been responding to some of the most common claims that are gaining traction on social media. Let's take a look at one. Disinformation: The provision of pencils at polling places by the AEC is part of a plan by the AEC, or officers of the AEC, to change the referendum result by rubbing out votes. This is the response from the AEC to that claim: The AEC provides pencils as they do not smudge when a ballot paper is folded, they can be stored and re-used from one event to the next, they don't run dry in tropical locations and they are cheaper than other implements. Voters are permitted to bring their own pen to mark the ballot paper with if they wish. Pencil marks are not erased. Polling officials are never alone with ballot papers - there are layers of supervision in place during the count and scrutineers are able to be present during counting. Suggestions of a conspiracy to overturn a referendum result by erasing ballot papers simply does not account for the transparency or scale of the process, let alone the history of high integrity Australian electoral events.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: AEC debunks claim pencils are provided at the polls so votes can be 'rubbed out'
